    medications: [{ name: "Barcode Medication Administration (BCMA) System", type: "Technology-based safety system", action: "Verifies five rights of medication administration (right patient, drug, dose, route, time) by scanning patient wristband barcode and medication barcode before administration; alerts nurse to discrepancies", sideEffects: "Alert fatigue from excessive warnings, workflow disruption if system is down, false sense of security if workarounds are used", contra: "System downtime requires manual verification procedures; do not administer medications without completing the barcode verification process", pearl: "BCMA reduces medication administration errors by 50–80% when used consistently; NEVER scan medications and then give them to the wrong patient; always scan at the bedside with the patient; report all system issues and workarounds to administration" }],
    pearls: ["If it wasn't documented, it wasn't done — legally, undocumented care is equivalent to unperformed care", "The Joint Commission 'Do Not Use' list includes: U (write 'units'), IU (write 'international units'), QD/QOD (write 'daily' or 'every other day'), trailing zeros (write 5 mg not 5.0 mg), lack of leading zero (write 0.5 mg not .5 mg), MS/MSO4/MgSO4 (write 'morphine sulfate' or 'magnesium sulfate')", "SBAR is the standard communication framework — using it consistently reduces communication errors and improves patient safety", "Never alter or backdate a medical record — this is fraud; if an error is made, follow institutional procedure for amendments (single line through error, initial, date, reason)", "HIPAA minimum necessary principle: Access only the patient information you NEED for the care you are providing; curiosity-based access is a violation even within your own facility", "Document patient refusals thoroughly: What was refused, education provided about risks of refusal, patient's stated reason, provider notification — this protects both the patient and the nurse legally"],
